did.abstract: Benjamin Kubelsky (1894-1974) was born in Chicago. He began his career as a violinist and turned to comedy in 1918. He was a successful vaudeville performer, actor and radio personality. The collection consists of radio and television scripts, photographs and production stills, personal and business records for the years 1935-1955 as well as magazines containing Benny articles, memorabilia, and awards.

bioghist.head: Biography
bioghist.p: Benjamin Kubelsky was born on February 14, 1894 in Chicago; raised in Waukegan, Illinois; began career as a violinist; turned to comedy in 1918, first as Ben K. Benny, then Jack Benny; became successful vaudeville performer during the 1920s, playing the Palace in New York City; married Sadye Marks (professionally known as Mary Livingstone) in 1927; made film debut in 1929, radio debut in 1932, television debut in 1950; became concert artist in 1956 and made frequent fund-raising appearances; died in Los Angeles, December 26, 1974.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: Collection consists of materials relating to the career of comedian Jack Benny. Includes radio and television scripts, photographs and production stills, personal and business records for the years 1935-1955, magazines containing Benny articles, memorabilia, and awards.

arrangement.head: Organization and Arrangement
arrangement.p:
Arranged in the following series:
Radio scripts (Boxes 1-42).
Television scripts (Boxes 42-57).
Tapes (Boxes 58-63).
Photographs (Boxes 64-79, 81).
Personal appearance materials 1948-1956 (Box 80).
Personal papers, correspondence, contracts (Boxes 82-98).
Serials (Boxes 90, 99).
Memorabilia, awards (Boxes 100-116).
Lucky Strike program scripts bound volumes (Boxes 117-120).

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Point of origin: NBC studios, Hollywood.

These Hollywood shows were recorded off the air (KFI) at 7:30-8:00 p.m. This is explained by the fact that the Benny programs, like many other radio shows of the period, were actually done twice, once for convenient listening in the eastern part of the country, then repeated for Western listeners 2 or 3 hours later.
Guests: Leo Robin and Ralph Ranger.

did.unittitle: 1. --Introductory program; reporter bit; Mary's tonsils; phone call from her doctor; Kenny's girl Lena; guest star, trans-Atlantic flyer; Anthony Adverse trailer..
2. --Jack reads wires and reviews on first broadcast; sketch - Anthony..
3. --Big broadcast of 1937, finishing with phone call from Dad; synopsis of first installment, Anthony Adverse; final Installment..
4. --Conceited routine; bit with Ben Blue; preview of Romeo and Juliet, finishing with phone call from Lawton Campbell; announcement of minstrel show..
5. --Halloween routine and election bit; minstrel show, finishing with Romeo and Juliet in blackface..
6. --Sensitive routine; Mary reads letter from her mother; schoolroom sketch, Girls dormitory with Patsy Flick..
7. --Finishes previous week's program; reminiscing routine about school days; Kenny's first anniversary - roller skates; start Buck Benny interrupted by Italian, policeman and lawyer..
8. --Palm Springs routine; Mary recites Thanksgiving poem; Phil arrives late - call from Carole Lombard; sketch - Buck Benny rides again..
9. --Courtesy routine; Jack does a Mae West on the phone, kidding Phil; announces English sketch but switches to Buck Benny..

10. --Filling station routine; Kenny comes in late with Phil, Jack refusing to talk to Phil; start their argument; Mary gets phone call from her mother; society drama, Money ain't everything (aboard yacht) which segues into Buck Benny..

11. --Jack is late for broadcast; tune in his home and Chinese valet answers; Jack comes up to studio looking for his hat; phone call from Lombard; Buck Benny - Andy Devine's first appearance on the program..

12. --Dual personality routine; Jack refuses to make up with Phil; recites poem, Bear it with a grin; Christmas presents; Patsy tries to sell Jack a suit; Phil presents Jack with platinum wrist watch..
13. --Christmas muffler gifts; Mary reads letter from her mother; Jack receives wire from all his radio friends; gives Phil one of his mufflers; Buck Benny rides again..
14. --New Year's routine; Baldwin but-in, finishing with whispering bit; Mary recites her New Year's poem; Kenny brings Lena up to the program; Buck Benny, finishing with Dr. Schmettena..
15. --Beginning of Fred Allen feud; Buckingham Benny, window dresser from Pomona; Buck Benny..

18. --Jack getting over his cold; race track bit; Mary reads a letter from her mother; Lucy Belle visits the studio, boy next door; dream bit, with Lind Hayes doing a Fred Allen; Jack wins radio editors' poll..
19. --Jack announces his intention to play The bee tonight; phone call to Lucy Belle; Andy Devine and Lena come over to hear Jack play, also Phil's mother and Lucy Belle; violin disappears!.
20. --Jack's birthday, gifts; Mary recites birthday poem; puts ad in paper asking for return of violin; Andy comes over with birthday present; guest star, Ben Bernie; he disappears!.
21. --Brewster's millions, Jack reads reviews; Mary goes highbrow; announces English drawing room drama but phone call from sponsor switches to Buck Benny; Mary leaves for New York for a rest..

22. --Jack reads letter from Mary; Lena visits Kenny again; Santa Anita handicap routine; Patsy Flick appears as detective, finding Jack's violin; Jack plays The bee which segues into Plenty of money; Jack talks to Mary on the phone; makes reservation to leave for New York..

23. --First broadcast from New York, from Waldorf-Astoria; Jack meets Abe Lyman, Abe gets tough; Schlepperman pays Jack a visit; Jack cross examines little 10 year old boy who played violin on Allen's program..

24. --Broadcast from Hotel Pierre; Mary reads wire from Kenny; Abe Lyman gets tough; income tax bit; Schlepperman volunteers to sing; Mary sings You do the darndest things, baby; Fred Allen pays Jack a visit, finishing up as friends, reminiscing about their old days together in vaudeville..

25. --Third and last broadcast from New York; Jack toots his horn; worn out from night clubs and the mad pace; Mayor Mancel Talcott Waukegan pays Jack a visit; department store sketch, Jack plays the part of his father..

26. --Scene in Chicago depot boarding train; routine on train, bit with colored porter, Albuquerque; Mary recites her Easter poem; routine with Indians at Albuquerque; Phil and Andy greet gang at studio..
27. --Spring routine; Jack starts fight with Phil - switches mood; Mary gets phone call from her mother; Andy and Jack - farm routine; annoucement of popular sketch to be repeated at later date..
28. --Jack's new suit routine; Mary reads letter from her mother (April Fool's day); guest star, Gracie Allen; Buck Benny with Gracie..
29. --Jack Benny (guest star) routine; Phil Harrises opening at the Cocoanut Grove; Andy Devine; English drawing room drama, Lady Millicent's husbands..
30. --Jack butts in during Phil's opening number - I demand an apology; guest stars, Block and Sully; Jack sends everyone home - visits Andy Devine's house in the country..

31. --Fifth anniversary program; Mary reads anniversary poem; Andy comes over to congratulate Jack; reporter bit finishing up with picture of cast; Buck Benny - party - song, Let's call the whole thing off..

32. --Mother's day routine; Jack starts fight with Phil; Kentucky Derby; Mary reads wire from her mother requesting schoolroom play; sketch; Jack announces results of popular play contest, trailer of Ah, wilderness..
33. --Vacation plans; announcement of sketch, Ah, wilderness..
34. --Jack did not broadcast because of illness..
35. --Sick-in-bed routine; Dr. Baldy - pills; Mary gets phone call from her mother; sketch, Murder at midnight..
36. --Jack reports that his watch is missing; colored fellow comes up to return it and claim rewards; sketch, Murder at midnight - interrupted by appearance of man from finance company..

37. --Jack boasts of his physical condition - exercise routine; Mary gets phone call from her producer at Paramount; Andy visits the program - sandwiches for the girls; Jack calls up his Artists producer re: Artists and models; scene on the Paramount lot; Mary shoots a scene..

38. --Father's day routine; Jack and nearsighted makeup man - also colored valet; synopsis of Artists and models; Jack plays his scene from inside a barrel - Hey!; In tag, guest star, Charlie Winninger..

39. --Jack complains about overwork; announces his trip to Europe; Pan-American Exposition, Dallas; sentimental bit; Mary sings, Love bug will bite you; guest star, Johnny Green; piano and violin duet, Body and soul; Farewell for season..
